'''''Enterobacteria phage Wphi''''' is a [[virus]] of the family [[Myoviridae]], genus ''[[P2-like viruses]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://talk.ictvonline.org/files/ictv_documents/m/msl/4090.aspx|title= Master Species List of 2011, version 2|author= [[International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses]] (ICTV) |year= 2011|accessdate=15 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|pmid=22481600|year=2012|last1=Adams|first1=MJ|last2=Carstens|first2=EB|title=Ratification vote on taxonomic proposals to the International Committee on Taxonomy of Viruses (2012)|volume=157|issue=7|pages=1411–22|doi=10.1007/s00705-012-1299-6|journal=Archives of Virology}}</ref>

As a member of the group I of the [[Baltimore classification]], ''Enterobacteria phage Wphi'' is a [[dsDNA virus]]es. All the members of family Myoviridae share a nonenveloped morphology consisting of a head and a tail separated by a neck. Its [[genome]] is linear. The propagation of the virions includes the attaching to a host cell (a [[bacterium]], as ''Enterobacteria phage Wphi'' is a [[bacteriophage]]) and the injection of the double stranded DNA; the host transcribes and translates it to manufacture new particles. To replicate its genetic content requires host cell [[DNA polymerases]] and, hence, the process is highly dependent on the cell cycle.<ref>{{cite journal|pmid=4329869|year=1971|last1=Baltimore|first1=D|title=Expression of animal virus genomes|volume=35|issue=3|pages=235–41|pmc=378387|journal=Bacteriological Reviews}}</ref>

