{{Redirect|Inis|the video game company|iNiS}} The '''International Nuclear Information System''' (INIS) hosts one of the world's largest collections of published information on the peaceful uses of nuclear science and technology.<ref name="unesco">{{cite web|url=http://www.unesco.org/new/en/communication-and-information/portals-and-platforms/goap/thematic-areas/sciences/international-nuclear-information-system-inis/ |title=International Nuclear Information System |publisher=[[Unesco]] |date= |accessdate=2012-05-30}}</ref>
==History== INIS is based in [[Vienna, Austria]] and has been operating since 1970.<ref name="unesco"/><ref name="stanford">{{cite web |url=http://lib.stanford.edu/engineering-library/international-nuclear-information-system-research-database-available |title=INIS research database available on-line |publisher=Stanford.edu |date=2009-04-14 |accessdate=2012-05-30 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120403084905/http://lib.stanford.edu/engineering-library/international-nuclear-information-system-research-database-available |archivedate=2012-04-03 |df= }}</ref> INIS is operated by the IAEA ([[International Atomic Energy Agency]]) in collaboration with 127 Member States and 24 co-operating international organizations.<ref name="unesco"/> All the content it holds is currently available free to "all Internet users around the world".<ref name="stanford"/>
==See also== *[[International Nuclear Event Scale]] (INES)
